ll of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:People from Montgomery County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Lincoln College (Illinois) alumni]]\n[[Category:Christians from Illinois]]\n[[Category:American hunters]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other people named Matthew or Matt Hughes|Matt Hughes (disambiguation){{!}}Matt Hughes}}\n{{short description|American UFC Hall of Famer, wrestler and mixed martial arts fighter}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Matt Hughes\n|\n| image           = Matt Hughes.png\n| image_size      =\n| alt             =\n| caption         = Matt Hughes in December 2007\n| birth_name      = Matthew Allen Hughes\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1973|10|13}}\n| birth_place     = [[Hillsboro, Illinois]], U.S.\n| residence       =\n| nationality     = American\n| height          = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}\n| weight_lb       = 170\n| weight_class    = [[Welterweight (MMA)|Welterweight]]\n| reach_in        = 73\n| style           = [[Wrestling]]\n| fighting_out_of = [[Hillsboro, Illinois]], U.S.\n| team            = [[Miletich Fighting Systems]] (1998\u20132007)<ref name=\"MFS\"/><br>[[Finney's HIT Squad]] (2007\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.sherdog.com/fighter/Matt-Hughes-232\n|title=Matt Hughes MMA Stats, Pictures, News, Videos, Biography\n|accessdate=2007-08-15\n|publisher=[[Sherdog]]\n}}</ref>\n| rank            = <!-- does not hold a martial art rank -->\n| wrestling       = NCAA Division I [[Collegiate wrestling|Wrestler]]\n| years_active    = 1998\u20132013\n| mma_kowin       = 17\n| mma_subwin      = 18\n| mma_decwin      = 10\n| mma_koloss      = 5\n| mma_subloss     = 4\n| mma_decloss     = \n| mma_draw        = \n| mma_nc          = \n| occupation      = \n| university      = [[Eastern Illinois University]] <br> [[Lincoln College, Illinois|Lincoln College]] <br> [[Southwestern Illinois College]]\n| spouse          = Audra Moore-Hughes\n| students        = \n| club            = \n| school          = \n| relatives       = [[Mark Hughes (fighter)|Mark Hughes]] (twin brother)\n| sherdog         = 232\n| footnotes       = [http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Matt-Hughes Official UFC Fighter Profile]<ref>Hughes' official website & Sherdog profile record one less win than his UFC profile. The record listed here represents the one given on his official website & Sherdog profile.</ref>\n| updated         =\n}}\n\n'''Matthew Allen Hughes''' (born October 13, 1973)<ref name=\"13 Oct 1973\" /> is an American retired mixed martial artist with a background in wrestling. Widely considered among the greatest fighters in the history of MMA, he is a two-time [[UFC Welterweight Championship|UFC Welterweight Champion]], [[UFC Hall of Fame|UFC Hall of Fame inductee]], and [[NJCAA#Halls of fame|NJCAA Hall of Fame inductee]].<ref name=\"Titles\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/articles/8/UFC-52-Couture-vs-Liddell-II-Preview-2666 |title=UFC 52: Couture vs. Liddell II Preview |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2005-04-13 |accessdate=2011-07-05}}</ref> During his tenures in the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]], Hughes put together two separate six-fight winning streaks, defeated all the available opposition in the [[Welterweight (MMA)|welterweight division]], and defended the belt a then-record seven times. Hughes was inducted into the [[UFC hall of fame#UFC Hall of Fame|UFC Hall of Fame]] in May 2010 during the UFC Fan Expo in conjunction with [[UFC 114]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.411mania.com/MMA/news/140561/Matt-Hughes-Inducted-Into-UFC-Hall-of-Fame.htm |title=Matt Hughes Inducted Into UFC Hall of Fame |publisher=411mania.com |author=Lambert, Jeremy |date=2010-05-20 |accessdate=2012-08-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203005430/http://www.411mania.com/MMA/news/140561/Matt-Hughes-Inducted-Into-UFC-Hall-of-Fame.htm |archive-date=2013-12-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Heavy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.heavy.com/mma/mma-news/2010/05/matt-hughes-inducted-into-ufc-hall-of-fame |title=Matt Hughes inducted into UFC Hall of Fame |author=Heavy MMA |accessdate=2012-06-30 |date=2010-05-29 |publisher=Heavy}}</ref><ref name=\"mmamania.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mmamania.com/2010/5/29/1492622/matt-hughes-inducted-into-ufc-hall |title=Matt Hughes inducted into UFC Hall of Fame |publisher=MMAmania.com |date=2010-05-29 |accessdate=2012-07-20 |last=Holland |first=Jesse}}</ref>\n\nDuring his reign, Hughes was widely considered the #1 [[Pound for pound|pound-for-pound]] [[mixed martial artist]] in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/117148-mma-history-of-the-pound-for-pound-best |title=A History of MMA's Pound-for-Pound Best |publisher=[[Bleacher Report]] |date=2009-01-29 |accessdate=2012-07-16 |author=Wiles, Mitch}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://mma.sbnation.com/2011/9/27/2451775/ufc-matt-hughes-best-fighter-welterweight-retires-mma-news/in/2219666 |title=Remembering Matt Hughes: The Best Fighter Of His Generation May Have Called It Quits |publisher=SB Nation |last=Snowden |first=Jonathan |date=2001-09-27 |accessdate=2012-07-16}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.wrestling101.com/101/article/JoeR/219/ |title=UFC 45: Revolution Review |publisher=Wrestling 101 |last=Reilly |first=Joe |date=2003-11-24 |accessdate=2012-09-03}}</ref> Hughes was also regarded by many analysts and several media outlets as one of the greatest welterweight fighters of all time, as well as one of the greatest pound-for-pound fighters in the sport's history.<ref name=\"bleacherreport.com\">{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/313619-mma-awards-of-the-decade/#/articles/313619-mma-awards-of-the-decade/page/12 |title=MMA Awards of the Decade |publisher=Bleacher Report |date=2009-12-23 |accessdate=2012-08-29}}</ref><ref name=\"About\">{{cite web |url=http://martialarts.about.com/od/mmaandufc/tp/topmmafightsdecade.htm |title=Top MMA Fights of the Decade |publisher=[[About.com]] |accessdate=2012-07-21 |last=Rousseau |first=Robert}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fighters.com/12/13/greatest-ufc-welterweight-of-all-time-the-arguments-for-georges-st-pierre-or-matt-hughes |title=Who is the Greatest Welterweight of All Time? |publisher=Fighters.com |date=2012-12-13 |accessdate=2012-04-07 |last=Rousseau |first=Robert |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101218103405/http://www.fighters.com/12/13/greatest-ufc-welterweight-of-all-time-the-arguments-for-georges-st-pierre-or-matt-hughes |archivedate=2010-12-18 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/864067-ufc-135-results-ranking-matt-hughes-greatest-career-moments#/articles/864067-ufc-135-results-ranking-matt-hughes-greatest-career-moments |title=UFC 135 Results: Ranking Hugues' Greatest Career moments |publisher=Bleacher Report |date=2011-09-27 |accessdate=2012-08-29 |last=Smith |first=Sean }}<br />{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mma/news?slug=ycn-10283069 |title=Hughes or GSP: Who is Greatest UFC Welterweight of All Time? Fan's Take |publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |author=Lopes, Hobson |date=2011-10-26 |accessdate=2012-08-29 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/454871-ufc-history-twenty-best-ufc-fighters-of-all-time#/articles/454871-ufc-history-twenty-best-ufc-fighters-of-all-time/page/22 |title=UFC History: 20 Best UFC Fighters Of All-Time |publisher=Bleacher Report |date=2010-09-11 |accessdate=2012-07-28 |last=Boyken |first=Joshua }}<br />{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/mma/fighter/122580/matt-hughes |title=Matt Hughes Fight News |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=2012-07-28 }}</ref><ref name=\"BR Hall of Fame\">{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/813729-ufc-ranking-chuck-liddell-and-the-ufc-hall-of-fame-inductees#/articles/813729-ufc-ranking-chuck-liddell-and-the-ufc-hall-of-fame-inductees/page/7 |title=Ranking Chuck Liddell and the UFC Hall of Fame inductees |publisher=Bleacher Report |date=2011-08-21 |accessdate=2012-08-29 |last=Fuller |first=Justin}}</ref>\n\nA long-time member of [[Miletich Fighting Systems]], Hughes left the Miletich camp in late 2007 to start Team Hughes.<ref name=\"MFS\">{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/2768/matt-hughes-to-start-fight-team-robbie-lawler-and-corey-hill-on-board.mma |title=Matt Hughes to Start Fight Team |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |accessdate=2012-07-28 |last=Stupp |first=Dann |date=2007-08-30 |authorlink=Dann Stupp |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113102235/http://mmajunkie.com/news/2768/matt-hughes-to-start-fight-team-robbie-lawler-and-corey-hill-on-board.mma |archivedate=2012-01-13 }}</ref> In 2008, Hughes published his autobiography, ''Made in America'', which made the [[New York Times bestseller list|''New York Times'' bestseller list]]. In 2011, Hughes became host of [[Outdoor Channel]]'s ''Trophy Hunters TV''. Hughes has no nickname, although because of his successes against [[Helio Gracie|Gracie]] [[Brazilian jiu-jitsu]] (BJJ) practitioners such as [[Royce Gracie]], [[Renzo Gracie]], [[Ricardo Almeida]], and [[Matt Serra]], people often refer to him as \"the Gracie Killer\" (the same as [[Kazushi Sakuraba|Sakuraba's]] nickname).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mma/blog/cagewriter/post/Hughes-has-no-interest-in-being-called-The-Grac?urn=mma,260778 |title=Hughes has no interest |publisher=sports.yahoo.com |accessdate=2010-08-06}}</ref> His mastery of submissions, and having submission wins over various black belt holders, are the reasons why [[Joe Rogan]] thinks he deserved to get a black belt for BJJ. Hughes never liked the idea, however, and considers himself primarily an amateur and submission [[Wrestling|wrestler]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sp7VNGgzJd0 Fight Night Goiania Free Fight: Thiago Alves vs. Matt Hughes]\n</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMatthew Allen Hughes was born on October 13, 1973, in [[Hillsboro, Illinois]].<ref name=\"born\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ufc.com/index.cfm?fa=fighter.detail&pid=4 |title=Fighter Detail&nbsp;\u2014 Matt Hughes |accessdate=2007-11-08 |publisher=Ultimate Fighting Championship |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071108093716/http://www.ufc.com/index.cfm?fa=fighter.detail&pid=4 |archivedate=2007-11-08 }}</ref> Hughes has two siblings, a sister and his twin brother, [[Mark Hughes (fighter)|Mark]]. During high school they both played [[American football|football]] and [[wrestling]].<ref name=\"mattchild\">{{cite web |url=http://www.matt-hughes.com/blog1/?page_id=617 |title=Biography & Testimony |accessdate=2007-11-08 |publisher=Matt-Hughes.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091214055614/http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/?page_id=617 |archivedate=2009-12-14 }}</ref> Hughes went to [[Southwestern Illinois College]] in Belleville, Illinois, before transferring to [[Lincoln College, Illinois|Lincoln College]], in [[Lincoln, Illinois]] and then on to [[Eastern Illinois University]] in [[Charleston, Illinois]].\n\n===Wrestling===\nHughes was a two-time 145&nbsp;lb IHSA ([[Illinois High School Association]]) Class A state wrestling champion. He won in 1991 and 1992 while attending [[Hillsboro High School (Illinois)]].<ref name=\"IHSA\" /> During his [[Junior year|junior]] and [[Senior (education)|senior]] years, Matt went undefeated and won back-to-back state championships in the 145&nbsp;lb class. Over the final three years of high school, he totaled 131 wins against only 2 losses, both during his [[Tenth grade#United States|sophomore]] year (sophomore 43-2; junior 43-0; senior 45-0).<ref name=\"mattchild\" />\n\nHis college career started at Southwestern Illinois College. Hughes placed fifth in the nation at 158&nbsp;lb. After Southwestern dropped their wrestling program, Hughes transferred to Lincoln College, where he placed third in the nation, notching a 33-3 record for the Lynx.<ref name=\"NJCAA career\" />\n\nAfter graduation Hughes continued wrestling at [[Eastern Illinois University]], where he was a two-time [[NCAA Division I]] [[All-American]] placing eighth in 1996 and fifth in 1997 at 158&nbsp;lb. He finished with an 80-15 record for Eastern Illinois.<ref name=\"NJCAA career\" />\n\nHughes competed in the prestigious [[ADCC Submission Wrestling World Championship]], in which he held a record of 2\u20132, beating [[Ricardo Almeida]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.forumeter.com/video/192578/Matt-Hughes-vs-Ricardo-Almeida-ADCC-2000 |title=Matt Hughes vs Ricardo Almeida-ADCC 2000 |publisher=Forumeter.com |accessdate=2012-08-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303232549/http://www.forumeter.com/video/192578/Matt-Hughes-vs-Ricardo-Almeida-ADCC-2000 |archive-date=2016-03-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[Jeremy Horn]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmaplayground.com/mma-videos/video/-matt-hughes-vs-jeremy-horn-adcc--1963.html |title= Matt Hughes vs. Jeremy Horn ADCC Fight |publisher=MMA Playground.com |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref> and losing to [[Jeff Monson]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adcombat.com/adcc-results?year=2000&weight=-99kg |title=ADCC 2000 Results |publisher=ADCC News |accessdate=2012-08-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519035046/http://www.adcombat.com/adcc-results?year=2000&weight=-99kg |archive-date=2012-05-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[Tito Ortiz]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mma-core.com/videos/other/ADCC_Tito_Ortiz_vs_Matt_Hughes/10000218 |title=ADCC 2000 Hughes vs Ortiz |accessdate=2012-08-26 |publisher=MMA-Core.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130303084305/http://www.mma-core.com/videos/other/ADCC_Tito_Ortiz_vs_Matt_Hughes/10000218 |archive-date=2013-03-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nHughes made his mixed martial arts debut on January 1, 1998 at Joe Gaytia's JKD Challenge. He slammed his opponent to the ground in just fifteen seconds, winning via KO.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mixedmartialarts.com/mma.cfm?go=stats.fightCard&eid=35b11684-d8f1-4d41-8cac-0009436e8bbb |title=JKD&nbsp;\u2014 Challenge 2 Official Results |publisher=MixedMartialArts.com |accessdate=2012-08-31}}</ref> The slam became his signature move.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cagepotato.com/10-best-signature-moves-mma |title=The 10 Best Signatures Moves in MMA |publisher=CagePotato.com |accessdate=2012-08-31}}</ref> He won his next fight via submission due to strikes. Hughes fought three times at Extreme Challenge 21, on October 17, 1998 defeating Victor Hunsaker via TKO and future [[UFC Middleweight Championship|UFC Midleweight Champion]] [[Dave Menne]] via unanimous decision. In the third fight of that night he lost to then-undefeated [[Dennis Hallman]] by technical submission (guillotine choke) at 0:17 of the first round. The result was announced as a KO.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mixedmartialarts.com/mma.cfm?go=stats.fightCard&eid=d130961a-44e5-4609-bb78-8efd4c9a0ac8#fight_3749 |title=Extreme Challenge 21 Official results |publisher=MixedMartialArts.com |accessdate=2012-08-31}}</ref> In the process, Hallman handed Hughes his first professional defeat.\n\n==Ultimate Fighting Championship==\nHughes made his promotional debut at ''[[UFC 22|UFC 22: There Can Be Only One Champion]]'', on September 24, 1999, defeating [[Bulgarians|Bulgarian]] Valeri Ignatov via unanimous decision after three rounds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-22-There-Can-Be-Only-One-Champion-32 |title=UFC 22-There Can Be Only One Champion |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-07-28}}</ref>\n\nHe returned to the promotion at ''[[UFC 26|UFC 26: Ultimate Field of Dreams]]'', where he defeated [[Marcelo Aguiar]] via TKO, throwing some elbows which cut Aguiar and forced the doctor to end the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/64864/History-of-the-UFC-12.10.07:-UFC-XXVI---Ultimate-Field-of-Dreams.htm |title=History of the UFC 12.10.07: UFC XXVI&nbsp;\u2014 Ultimate Field of Dreams |publisher=411mania.com |last=McEwen |first=Matt |date=2007-12-10 |accessdate=2012-09-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607060853/http://www.411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/64864/History-of-the-UFC-12.10.07%3A-UFC-XXVI---Ultimate-Field-of-Dreams.htm |archivedate=2011-06-07 }}</ref> The stoppage came at 4:34 of the first round.\n\nHughes faced [[Dennis Hallman]] in a rematch at ''[[UFC 29|UFC 29: Defense of the Belts]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-29-Defense-of-the-Belts-39 |title=UFC 29 - Defense of the Belts |accessdate=2012-09-03 |publisher=Sherdog.com}}</ref> At this point in their careers, Hallman was the only man to have defeated Hughes in MMA competition. Hughes lost the fight via armbar in only twenty seconds. When the bout started, Hughes lifted and brutally slammed Hallman to the mat, but was caught in the submission after landing in side-control.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/66429/History-of-the-UFC-01.07.07:-UFC-XXIX---Defense-of-the-Belts.htm |title=History of the UFC 01.07.07: UFC XXIX&nbsp;\u2014 Defense of the Belts |publisher=411mania.com |accessdate=2012-09-03 |date=2008-01-07 |last=McEwen |first=Matt |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306074043/http://411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/66429/History-of-the-UFC-01.07.07:-UFC-XXIX---Defense-of-the-Belts.htm |archive-date=2012-03-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Welterweight championship===\n\nHughes won his first UFC World Welterweight title at ''[[UFC 34|UFC 34: High Voltage]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mma/news?slug=dm-ufcthirtyfour050609 |title=UFC 34: Hughes is crowned |last=Meltzer |first=Dave |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |date=2009-05-06 |accessdate=2012-09-03}}</ref> on November 2, 2001. In a come-from-behind fight, Hughes was caught in a [[triangle choke]] by then-champion [[Carlos Newton]], but he lifted Newton in the air and slammed him to the mat,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/70178/History-of-the-UFC-03.03.08:-UFC-XXXIV---High-Votlage.htm |title=History of the UFC 03.03.08: UFC XXXIV&nbsp;\u2014 High Votlage |publisher=411mania.com |last=McEwen |first=Matt |accessdate=2012-09-03 |date=2008-03-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306074203/http://411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/70178/History-of-the-UFC-03.03.08:-UFC-XXXIV---High-Votlage.htm |archive-date=2012-03-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> causing Newton to hit his head and lose consciousness just as Hughes was himself on the verge of blacking out from the choke. After the match Newton stated that he felt the reason Hughes fell to the mat was because he was rendered unconscious from the triangle choke.<ref name=\"renamed_from_34_on_20120903234906\" /> This was confirmed by Hughes himself upon reviewing the tape of the match Hughes can be heard telling his corner after the fight \"I was out\".<ref name=\"renamed_from_34_on_20120903234906\">{{cite video |title=[[UFC 34|UFC 34: High Voltage]] |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] |location=[[Paradise, Nevada]], [[United States]] |date=2001-11-02}}</ref>\nThe result was officially announced as a KO at 1:27 of the second round. The slam is considered to be one of the greatest in [[Mixed martial arts|MMA]] history.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/687422-ufc-130-rampage-jackson-and-the-6-most-devastating-slams-in-mma-history#/articles/687422-ufc-130-rampage-jackson-and-the-6-most-devastating-slams-in-mma-history/page/4 |title=Rampage Jackson and the 6 Most Devastating Slams in MMA History |publisher=BleacherReport.com |last=Carey |first=Vince |date=2011-05-02 |accessdate=2012-09-03}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://weheartmma.com/post/853036101/top-5-best-mma-slams-of-all-time |title=Top 5 Best Slams of All-Time |publisher=WeHeartMMA.com |accessdate=2012-09-03}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.cagepotato.com/seven-most-brutal-ko-slams-mma-history/ |title=The Seven Most Brutal KO Slams in MMA History |publisher=CagePotato.com |accessdate=2012-09-03}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1261361-25-best-championship-fights-in-ufc-history#/articles/1261361-25-best-championship-fights-in-ufc-history/page/9 |title=25 Best Championship Fights in UFC History |publisher=BleacherReport.com |last=Snowden |first=Jonathan |date=2012-07-17 |accessdate=2012-09-03}}</ref>\n\nHe successfully defended his championship belt at ''[[UFC 36|UFC 36: Worlds Collide]]'', defeating former [[List of Shooto champions#Middleweight Championship|Shooto Middleweight Champion]] [[Hayato Sakurai]] via TKO due to strikes at 3:01 of the fourth round.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-36-Worlds-Collide-771 |title=UFC 36 - Worlds Collide |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-03}}</ref> In the first round of the fight, Hughes spent all the time either clinching Sakurai up against the fence, or ripping his feet out from under him.<ref name=\"History of UFC XXXVI\">{{cite web |url=http://411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/71566/History-of-the-UFC-03.24.08:-UFC-XXXVI---Worlds-Collide.htm |title=History of the UFC 03.24.08: UFC XXXVI&nbsp;\u2014 Worlds Collide |publisher=411mania.com |date=2008-03-24 |last=McEwen |first=Matt |accessdate=2012-09-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306074211/http://411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/71566/History-of-the-UFC-03.24.08:-UFC-XXXVI---Worlds-Collide.htm |archive-date=2012-03-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In round 2, Sakurai landed a right hand that sent Hughes to the mat; despite this, Matt won the round by spending three minutes hitting Sakurai with elbows from the top position.<ref name=\"History of UFC XXXVI\" /> At the start of the third round, Hughes quickly slammed Sakurai to the ground, again staying three minutes on top. He looked too strong for Sakurai.<ref name=\"History of UFC XXXVI\" /> Hughes finished the bout in the 4th round, by taking down Sakurai and transitioning to [[full mount]]. After one minute of [[Ground and pound|ground-and-pound]] onslaught, the contest was over as Sakurai had no answer for the champion.<ref name=\"History of UFC XXXVI\" />\n\nHughes faced [[Carlos Newton]] in their subsequent rematch at the main event of ''[[UFC 38|UFC 38: Brawl at the Hall]]'', in the promotion's debut in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mma/news?slug=dm-ufcthirtyeight050909 |title=UFC 38: Brawls in and out of the Hall |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |last=Meltzer |first=Dave |date=2009-05-09 |accessdate=2012-07-21}}</ref> He won the fight by technical knockout when he successfully trapped Newton in a modified [[crucifix position]], which allowed him to rain unanswered blows on Newton's face until the referee stopped the contest at 3:27 of round 4.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tapology.com/fightcenter/bouts/ufc-38-matt-hughes-vs-carlos-the-ronin-newton-ii-2 |title=Matt Hughes vs. Carlos Newton II, UFC 38 |publisher=Tapology.com |accessdate=2012-07-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-38-Brawl-at-the-Hall-923 |title=UFC 38 - Brawl at the Hall |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-03}}</ref>\n\nIn his next title defense, Hughes fought [[Gil Castillo]] at ''[[UFC 40|UFC 40: Vendetta]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-40-Vendetta-1220 |title=UFC 40 - Vendetta |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-03}}</ref> defeating the former [[Middleweight (MMA)|Middleweight]] contender via TKO. Hughes started the match with a big slam and then began to attack from Castillo's guard with elbows and punches. Hughes easily avoided any submission attempts and looked far stronger than Castillo. As he passed to half guard, Castillo was bleeding above his left eye. The challenger's only offense was a weak triangle choke that went nowhere. The round ended with Hughes on top, ground-and-pounding his opponent.<ref name=\"review40\">{{cite web |url=http://411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/75287/History-of-the-UFC-05.12.08:-UFC-XL---Vendetta.htm |title=History of the UFC 05.12.08: UFC XL&nbsp;\u2014 Vendetta |publisher=411mania.com |last=McEwen |first=Matt |date=2008-05-12 |accessdate=2012-09-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306074330/http://411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/75287/History-of-the-UFC-05.12.08:-UFC-XL---Vendetta.htm |archive-date=2012-03-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Between rounds doctors ruled that the resulting cut was too severe to continue, and Hughes was declared the winner due to stoppage.<ref name=\"review40\" />\n\nAt ''[[UFC 42|UFC 42: Sudden Impact]]'', Hughes faced future [[UFC Lightweight Championship|UFC Lightweight Champion]] [[Sean Sherk]], winning via unanimous decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-42-Sudden-Impact-1469 |title=UFC 42 - Sudden Impact |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-03}}</ref> Hughes started the action by taking Sherk down immediately, passing to half guard. Sherk was able to stand for a few seconds before Hughes took him down again.<ref name=\"History of the UFC XLII\">{{cite web |url=http://411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/77444/History-of-the-UFC-06.09.08:-UFC-XLII:-Sudden-Impact.htm |title=History of the UFC 06.09.08: UFC XLII: Sudden Impact |publisher=411mania.com |last=McEwen |first=Matt |date=2008-06-09 |accessdate=2012-09-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306074345/http://411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/77444/History-of-the-UFC-06.09.08:-UFC-XLII:-Sudden-Impact.htm |archive-date=2012-03-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In round two, they started to trade punches, but eventually Hughes took Sherk down. Like the first round, they stood up for a moment.<ref name=\"History of the UFC XLII\" /> At the beginning of the third round, Sherk took Hughes down, while Hughes attempted a kimura from the bottom. A late stand up led to a second takedown by Sherk.<ref name=\"History of the UFC XLII\" /> Round 4 saw Hughes using his strength to control the challenger on the ground. Sherk took Hughes down again in the fifth round, but the champion controlled the rest of the time sprawl-and-brawling as he finished on top.<ref name=\"History of the UFC XLII\" /> With the victory, he became the first man to defeat Sherk.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mma/news?slug=dm-ufcfortytwo0514 |title=UFC 42:Wrestler vs. Wrestler |last=Meltzer |first=Dave |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |date=2009-05-14 |accessdate=2012-07-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/fighter/Sean-Sherk-277 |title=Sean \"The Muscle Shark Sherk MMA Stats, Pictures, New, Videos, Biography |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-04}}</ref>\n\nHughes faced former [[World Fighting Alliance|WFA]] Welterweight Champion [[Frank Trigg]] at the main event of ''[[UFC 45|UFC 45: Revolution]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-45-Revolution-1863 |title=UFC 45 - Revolution |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-03}}</ref> This event marked the UFC's 10th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mma/news?slug=dd-ufcfortyfive051509 |title=UFC 45: Hall of Fame is born |last=Doyle |first=Dave |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |date=2012-05-16 |accessdate=2012-07-21}}</ref> After a tactical grappling match-up early on, Trigg fell victim to a standing rear naked choke at 3:45 of the first round.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/articles/UFC-45-Revolution-Review-1300 |title=UFC 45 - Revolution Review |publisher=Sherdog.com |last=Savage |first=Greg |date=2003-11-21 |accessdate=2012-09-03}}</ref> The choke earned Hughes the ''Tapout of the Night Submission Award''.<ref name=\"Titles & Awards\">{{cite web |url=http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/?page_id=626 |title=Titles & Awards |last=Hughes |first=Matt |publisher=Matt-Hughes.com |accessdate=2012-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625083222/http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/?page_id=626 |archivedate=2012-06-25 }}</ref>\n\n===Loss to Penn and regaining the title===\nHe kept the title until ''[[UFC 46|UFC 46: Supernatural]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-46-Supernatural-1943 |title=UFC 46 - Supernatural |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-04}}</ref> when he was submitted by [[Native Hawaiians|Hawaiian]] [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu]] specialist [[B.J. Penn]] via [[rear naked choke]] at 4:39 of the first round,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tapology.com/fightcenter/bouts/ufc-46-bj-the-prodigy-penn-vs-matt-hughes-i-1 |title=BJ Penn vs. Matt Hughes I |publisher=Tapology.com |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref> in a fight he was heavily favored to win.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/80139/History-of-the-UFC-07.14.08:-UFC-XLVI---Supernatural.htm |title=History of the UFC 07.14.08: UFC XLVI&nbsp;\u2014 Supernatural |accessdate=2012-07-17 |publisher=411mania.com |date=2008-07-14 |last=McEwen |first=Matt |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130417074253/http://www.411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/80139/History-of-the-UFC-07.14.08:-UFC-XLVI---Supernatural.htm |archive-date=2013-04-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The title was vacated upon a contract dispute between Penn and the UFC, which promptly stripped him of the welterweight title, claiming Penn had breached his contract and that the signing constituted him refusing to defend his title. Penn filed suit against UFC and publicized his side of the conflict, claiming his contract had expired. Penn filed a motion to stop UFC from awarding a new welterweight title, but that motion was denied.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/BJ-Penn-Sues-Zuffa-Over-Stripping-of-Welterweight-Title-1872 |title=BJ Penn sues Zuffa over Stripping of Welterweight title |last=Sloan |first=Mike |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2004-07-23 |accessdate=2012-07-17}}</ref>\n\nHughes faced Penn's training partner [[Renato Verissimo]] at ''[[UFC 48|UFC 48: Payback]]'', winning via unanimous decision (30-27; 30-27; 29-28).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-48-Payback-2203 |title=UFC 48 - Payback |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-04}}</ref> He was caught in a very tight [[triangle choke]] in the first round,<ref name=\"Payback\">{{cite web |url=http://www.411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/83009/History-of-the-UFC-08.18.08:-UFC-XLVIII:-Payback.htm |title=History of the UFC 08.18.08: UFC XLVI&nbsp;\u2014 Supernatural |accessdate=2012-09-04 |publisher=411mania.com |date=2008-08-18 |last=McEwen |first=Matt |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130417085227/http://www.411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/83009/History-of-the-UFC-08.18.08:-UFC-XLVIII:-Payback.htm |archive-date=2013-04-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but after winning the second and third rounds, was awarded with the victory.<ref name=\"Payback\" />\n\nHughes regained the vacant welterweight title by submitting [[Canadians|Canadian]] contender [[Georges St-Pierre]] via armbar in the final second of the first round at ''[[UFC 50|UFC 50: The War of '04]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-50-The-War-of-04-2512 |title= UFC 50 - The War of '04 |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-04}}</ref> The fight was competitive. Hughes took GSP down twice and landed a huge slam. Hughes was in trouble at the beginning of the bout as St-Pierre unloaded a spinning back kick into his ribs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/166141/Falcons-Nest-DVD-Review---UFC-50.htm |title=Falcons Nest DVD Review&nbsp;\u2014 UFC 50 |publisher=411mania.com |date=2010-12-15 |accessdate=2012-09-04 |last=Andrews |first=Kile |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030060642/http://www.411mania.com/MMA/video_reviews/166141/Falcons-Nest-DVD-Review---UFC-50.htm |archive-date=2012-10-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The submission earned Hughes his second ''Tapout of the Night''.<ref name=\"Titles & Awards\" /> Obviously disappointed at the time, St. Pierre admitted afterward that he had lost before he ever stepped into the Octagon. He had regarded Hughes as his idol, not as someone he could beat.<ref name=\"GSP Afraid\" />\n\nHughes successfully retained his title against Trigg in their historic rematch at ''[[UFC 52|UFC 52: Couture vs. Liddell 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-52-Couture-vs-Liddell-2-2930 |title=UFC 52 - Couture vs. Liddell 2 |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-04}}</ref> Accidentally hit in the groin early in the first round, Hughes looked to the referee for assistance; however, the referee had not seen the strike and Trigg capitalized on Hughes' distraction by staggering him with a barrage of punches. The fight quickly went to the ground, with Trigg ground-and-pounding Hughes, then attempting a rear naked choke. After nearly two minutes of struggling, Hughes broke free, picked Trigg up, carried him across the Octagon and slammed him to the ground. Hughes then ground-and-pounded Trigg before securing the victory with a rear naked choke of his own, in what is considered one of the UFC's greatest fights.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmamania.com/2011/11/24/2584537/post-139-top-5-bouts-in-the-organizations-history |title=Top 5 UFC fights in the promotion's modern history |publisher=MMAmania.com |date=2011-11-24 |accessdate=2012-07-28 |last=Mette |first=Dia}}</ref> and comebacks in MMA history.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://weheartmma.com/post/928159538/top-10-best-mma-comeback-wins-of-all-time |title=Top 10 Best MMA Comeback wins of All-Time |publisher=WeHeartMMA.com |accessdate=2012-09-04}}</ref><ref name=\"dana\">{{cite web |url=http://mma.sbnation.com/2011/9/29/2458037/ufc-52-matt-hughes-ufc-history-news-arch-nemesis-frank-trigg |title=UFC 52: Matt Hughes Survives To Defeat Arch Nemesis Frank Trigg |publisher=SBNation.com |last=Snowden |first=Jonathan |accessdate=2012-07-23 |date=2011-09-29}}</ref> This fight is UFC President Dana White's favorite match in combat sport history.<ref name=\"dana\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mensfitness.com/training/pro-tips/ufc%E2%80%99s-10-greatest-fights?page=3 |title=UFC's 10 Greatest Fights |accessdate=2012-07-17 |last=Murphy |first=Ryan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fightsincage.com/10-greatest-moments-in-ufc-history/ |title=10 Greatest Moments In UFC History |publisher=FightsInCage.com |last=O'Farrell |first=Liam |accessdate=2012-09-04}}</ref> He was awarded the ''Tapout of the Night'' for the third time in his career.<ref name=\"Titles & Awards\" />\n\nHughes' next fight took place at ''[[UFC 56|UFC 56: Full Force]]'', where he was scheduled to fight [[Judo]] practitioner [[Karo Parisyan]]. After Parysian suffered a [[hamstring]] injury and could not fight,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tapology.com/fightcenter/bouts/ufc-56-matt-hughes-vs-karo-the-heat-parisyan |title=UFC 56: Hughes vs Parisyan |publisher=Tapology.com |accessdate=2012-09-04}}</ref> [[Joe Riggs]] took his place.<ref name=\"ev56\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-56-Full-Force-3328 |title=UFC 56 - Full Force |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-04}}</ref> The match was originally scheduled as a title bout, but since Riggs could not meet the 170-pound weight limit, it became a non-title fight.<ref name=\"Failed Weight\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Riggs146s-Failed-WeighIn-Makes-UFC-History-3659 |title=Riggs's Failed Weigh-In Makes UFC History |last=Gross |first=Josh |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2005-11-19 |accessdate=2012-09-04}}</ref> It marked the first time for the UFC that a title fight had to be called off for this reason.<ref name=\"Failed Weight\" />\n\n{{quote|I'm not disappointed. It makes me a lot more relaxed to go in there. I don't have pressure of possibly losing my title. I think it's great news for me. I mean the only thing I don't like about it is it's a three-round fight and I've trained for five rounds.<ref name=\"Failed Weight\"/>}}\n\nHughes defeated Riggs in the first round by submission via [[Armlock#Kimura|kimura]] from the half-guard at 3:28.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://angrymarks.com/?ArticleID=15226 |title=UFC 56: Hughes vs. Riggs, Franklin vs. Quarry |publisher=AngryMarks.com |date=2005-11-19 |accessdate=2012-09-06}}</ref> The armlock earned Hughes his last ''Tapout of the Night'' award.<ref name=\"Titles & Awards\" /><ref name=\"ev56\" />\n\n{{Quote box| quote = We knew what he was planning to do. We worked out his game plan before the fight, and he did exactly what we expected. I over-trained for the fight. That was all. I started training too much, too hard, for too long. He did exactly what we expected.|align=right |width=40%|source=-[[Royce Gracie]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmaweekly.com/royce-gracie-wants-a-rematch-with-matt-hughes |title=- ROYCE GRACIE WANTS A REMATCH WITH MATT HUGHES |publisher=MMAWeekly.com |accessdate=2012-07-28 |date=2006-08-10 |author=Staff}}</ref>}}\n\nAt ''[[UFC 60|UFC 60: Hughes vs. Gracie]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-60-Hughes-vs-Gracie-3666 |title=UFC 60 - Hughes vs. Gracie |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-04}}</ref> on May 27, 2006, Hughes defeated [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu]] legend and [[UFC Hall of Fame]]r [[Royce Gracie]] in a non-title, catch-weight bout by TKO (strikes) at 4:39 of the first round.<ref name=\"UFC 60 Play-by-play\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-60-Hughes-vs-Gracie-PlaybyPlay-4566 |title=UFC 60 \"Hughes vs Gracie\" Play-by-Play |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2006-05-27 |accessdate=2012-09-05}}</ref> Before the stoppage, Gracie was caught in an [[armlock]] from the [[Side control|side mount]] position;<ref name=\"UFC 60 Play-by-play\" /> although Hughes appeared to have the submission in place, Gracie would not tap out. Hughes stated that he felt his arm pop and realized he would never tap, so instead of breaking his arm, opted to seek a different position .<ref>{{cite web |url=http://voices.yahoo.com/royce-gracie-wants-rematch-against-matt-hughes-8441083.html?cat=14 |title=Royce gracie wants rematch with Matt Hughes |date=2011-06-24 |publisher=Yahoo.com |accessdate=2014-04-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416183223/http://voices.yahoo.com/royce-gracie-wants-rematch-against-matt-hughes-8441083.html?cat=14 |archive-date=2014-04-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The event drew 620,000 buys, becoming the best-selling [[pay-per-view]] in UFC history, and was the first to break the $20 million mark in gross PPV sales.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dev.mmaweekly.com/ufc-61-surpasses-30-million-in-ppv-sales-2 |title=UFC 61 SURPASSES $30 MILLION IN PPV SALES |date=2006-09-06 |publisher=MMAWeekly.com |last=Trembow |first=Ivan |accessdate=2012-07-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202115307/http://dev.mmaweekly.com/ufc-61-surpasses-30-million-in-ppv-sales-2 |archivedate=2014-02-02 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|It just seemed like I was a step ahead of him. I was really surprised. I was [also] surprised by the strength difference, and especially when I was on the ground with him. Wherever I wanted his hand, I put it there. I really shouldn't be able to do that with somebody as talented as Royce.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.extremeprosports.com/full_contact_fighting/hughes_vs_gracie_winner.html |title=Matt Hughes vs Royce Gracie&nbsp;\u2014 How the Battle of Champions Went Down |last=Montgomery |first=Cliff |publisher=ExtremeProSports.com |accessdate=2012-09-05}}</ref>}}\n[[Image:HughesPenn-faceoff.jpg|right|thumb|180px|Hughes and Penn at the weigh-ins before their rematch at [[UFC 63|UFC 63: Hughes vs. Penn]].]]\n\nHughes was scheduled to fight [[Georges St-Pierre]] in a rematch at ''[[UFC 63]]'',<ref name=\"St-Pierre injured\">{{cite web |url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/2006/08/prweb428836.htm |title=St. Pierre Out, Penn in Against Hughes at UFC 63 |publisher=Prweb.com |date=2006-08-26 |accessdate=2012-07-28 |last=Myers |first=Thomas}}</ref><ref name=\"GSP injured\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.sympatico.ca/ActionSports/Articles/StPierre_out.htm |title=St. Pierre Sidelined by Injury; 'The Prodigy' to The Rescue |publisher=Sympatico.ca |date=2006-08-15 |last=Gerbasi |first=Thomas |accessdate=2012-09-05}}</ref> but after St-Pierre sustained a severe groin injury, the UFC announced that [[B.J. Penn]] would replace him in the title fight.<ref name=\"St-Pierre injured\" /><ref name=\"GSP injured\" /> At this point in their careers, Penn was the only mixed martial artist to beat Hughes after March 2001. In fact, it was Hughes' only loss in his last 19 fights.<ref name=\"St-Pierre injured\" /> In the bout, Penn controlled the first two rounds,<ref name=\"UFC 63 Play-by-play\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-63-Hughes-vs-Penn-PlaybyPlayPresented-by-Sprawl-Fight-Short-Company-5662 |title=UFC 63 \"Hughes vs Penn\" Play-by-Play |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2006-09-23 |accessdate=2012-09-05}}</ref><ref name=\"HuPe2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mmaweekly.com/ufc-63-review-hughes-beats-penn-in-a-classic |title=- UFC 63 REVIEW: HUGHES BEATS PENN IN A CLASSIC |publisher=MMAWeekly.com |date=2006-09-24 |accessdate=2012-09-06 |last=Martin |first=Damon}}</ref> but sustained a rib injury during the scramble to take Hughes' back in round two. He was visibly different in the third round, appearing exhausted and missing punches he was landing earlier. Hughes was able to take Penn to the mat, and in side-control [[crucifix position]] rained punches on Penn's head until referee [[John McCarthy (mixed martial arts)|\"Big\" John McCarthy]] stopped the fight at 3:53 of the third round.<ref name=\"UFC 63 Play-by-play\" /><ref name=\"HuPe2\" /> In the process, Hughes became the first man to ever stop Penn in a fight.<ref name=\"UFC 63 Play-by-play\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/fighter/BJ-Penn-1307 |title=B.J. \"The Prodigy\" Penn MMA Stats, Pictures, News, Videos, Biography |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-05}}</ref> Both fighters were awarded the ''Fight of the Night'' bonus.<ref name=\"FotN 1\">{{cite web |url=http://hosteddb.fightmetric.com/fights/index/461 |title=UFC 63: Hughes vs. Penn |publisher=FightMetric |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> In an interview on Penn's personal website, Penn stated that by round three he could hardly breathe and had no \"mobility in his core\".<ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mmanews.com/news/79814 |title=B.J. Penn Claims Rib Injury Influenced Loss To Matt Hughes |publisher=MMANews.com |accessdate=2012-06-27 |date=2006-09-28}}</ref>  Despite the injury, Penn congratulated Hughes, calling him a great fighter and saying he deserved the victory.<ref name=\"Interview\" /> \n\n{{Quote box|You are the greatest champion of all time.|align=left |width=40%|source=-[[Dana White]] told Hughes in the cage at UFC 63.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mma.sbnation.com/2011/9/29/2457645/ufc-63-matt-hughes-ufc-history-revenge-on-bj-penn/in/2219666 |title=UFC 63: Matt Hughes Gets Revenge On B.J. Penn |publisher=SBNation.com |last=Snowden |first=Jonathan |date=2011-09-29 |accessdate=2012-07-16}}</ref>}} \n\nSt-Pierre stepped into the ring to promote his upcoming title fight against Hughes, stating that he was glad that Hughes won his fight, but that he was \"not impressed\" by Hughes' performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmamania.com/2008/11/07/georges-st-pierre-im-not-impressed-with-your-performance-video/ |title=Georges St-Pierre \"I'm not impressed by your performance\" video |publisher=MMAmania.com |date=2008-11-07 |format=video |accessdate=2009-02-04 |author=Staff}}</ref> According to both commentator Joe Rogan and Hughes' own autobiography, Hughes was unhappy with St-Pierre's statement. Hughes said that they \"had words\" off-camera shortly thereafter. St-Pierre apologized, saying he had misunderstood something Hughes had said on the microphone and did not mean to offend him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.betus.com.pa/sports-betting/ufc/articles/ufc-65-canada-vs-the-usa/ |title=UFC 65 - Canada Vs. The USA |publisher=BetUS.com |last=O'Cairbre |first=Eamon |accessdate=2012-09-05 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Loss to St-Pierre===\nOn November 18, 2006, at ''[[UFC 65|UFC 65: Bad Intentions]]'', Georges St-Pierre defeated Hughes by TKO via strikes at 1:25 of round two, ending Hughes' title reign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-65-Bad-Intentions-4313 |title=UFC 65 - Bad Intentions |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-08-31}}</ref> In the first round, Hughes sustained two unintentional kicks near the groin; after Hughes went down from the second kick, St-Pierre was given a warning by referee [[John McCarthy (referee)|\"Big\" John McCarthy]].<ref name=\"sherdog.com\">{{cite web|title=UFC 65 \"Bad Intentions\" Play-by-Play|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-65-Bad-Intentions-PlaybyPlayPresented-by-Sprawl-Fight-Short-Company-6171|publisher=Sherdog.com|accessdate=2012-08-31|date=2006-11-18}}</ref> However, Hughes stated in the post-fight interview that the second kick mainly affected his legs, rather than his groin.<ref>\"''The second time I went down, it wasn't really because of my groin, but it affected my legs more than my groin. I don't know if it's a nerve thing or what happened.''\" Matt Hughes, UFC 65 post-fight press conference.</ref> Nearing the end of the first round, St-Pierre landed a [[Superman punch]], which floored Hughes. St-Pierre then followed up with strikes on his stunned opponent. When it appeared that the fight would be stopped, the bell rang signaling the end of the first round. In the second round St-Pierre ended the fight with a head kick which stunned Hughes and knocked him to the mat. He followed up with a flurry of punches and elbows that forced McCarthy to stop the contest with 3:35 left in the round.<ref name=\"sherdog.com\" />\n\n===Return===\nOn March 3, 2007, Hughes returned to the Octagon for ''[[UFC 68|UFC 68: Uprising]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-68-Uprising-4662 |title=UFC 68 - Uprising |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-05}}</ref> defeating [[Chris Lytle]] by unanimous decision, winning 30\u201327 on all three judges' scorecards.<ref name=\"Sh\" /> Hughes secured an armbar at the end of round one, but Lytle was saved by the bell. Hughes opened the second round with a quick takedown, moving up to side-control and then landed an elbow that cut Lytle. Finally, Hughes mounted his opponent, but Lytle swept and was able to reverse that position. In the third round, Hughes unsuccessfully tried an armbar again before the horn sounded.<ref name=\"Sh\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-68-The-Uprising-PlaybyPlayPresented-by-Sprawl-Fight-Short-Company-6884 |title=UFC 68 \"The Uprising\" Play-by-Play\n|publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2007-03-03 |accessdate=2012-08-31}}</ref>\n\nIn late mid-2007, Hughes left the [[Miletich Fighting Systems|Miletich camp]] with Miletich stablemate [[Robbie Lawler]], longtime [[boxing]] coach Matt Pena, and [[wrestling]]/[[Aerobic conditioning|conditioning]] teacher Marc Fiore to form The H.I.T. (Hughes Intensive Training) Squad in [[Granite City, Illinois]].<ref name=\"MFS\" />\n\n===''The Ultimate Fighter ''===\nIn 2005, Hughes participated as a coach opposite [[Rich Franklin]] in the [[The Ultimate Fighter 2|second season]] of the [[Spike TV]] [[reality television]] series, ''[[The Ultimate Fighter]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmaweekly.com/season-2-coaches-on-ultimate-fighter |title=Season 2 Coaches On Ultimate Fighter |publisher=MMAWeekly.com |date=2005-08-23 |accessdate=2012-09-06 |author=Staff}}</ref> This was the first season where the coaches did not fight each other after the conclusion of the show, because Franklin and Hughes were champions in different weight divisions. In 2007, Hughes participated as a guest coach for long-time friend and training partner, [[Jens Pulver]] during ''[[The Ultimate Fighter 5]]'' season.\n\nHughes agreed to head coach again for ''[[The Ultimate Fighter 6]]'', alongside then-[[UFC Welterweight Champion]], [[Matt Serra]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmamania.com/2007/04/21/tuf-6-matt-serra-and-matt-hughes-named-as-coaches/ |title=TUF 6: Matt Serra and Matt Hughes named as coaches |publisher=MMAmania.com |date=2007-04-21 |accessdate=2012-08-31 |last=Holland |first=Jesse}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Serra-Hughes-to-Coach-TUF-6-7325 |title=Serra, Hughes to Coach TUF 6 |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2007-04-21 |accessdate=2012-09-08 |author=Staff}}</ref> Despite the fact that after the preliminary round, Team Hughes' record was 2\u20136, both [[Mac Danzig]] and [[Tommy Speer]] of Team Hughes made it to the finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-The-Ultimate-Fighter-6-Finale-5459 |title=UFC&nbsp;\u2014 The Ultimate Fighter 6 Finale |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/articles/1/145TUF-6146-Down-to-Danzig-Speer-10286 |title='TUF 6' Down to Danzig, Speer |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2007-12-08 |accessdate=2012-09-08}}</ref> In 2011, Hughes appeared as guest coach during ''[[The Ultimate Fighter 13]]'' season for friend and former [[UFC Heavyweight Championship|UFC Heavyweight Champion]] [[Brock Lesnar]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/603478-brock-lesnars-team-trains-with-matt-hughes-for-the-ultimate-fighter-13 |title=Brock Lesnar's Team Trains With Matt Hughes for the Ultimate Fighter 13 |publisher=Bleacher Report |date=2011-02-15 |accessdate=2012-09-06 |last=Horne |first=Leon}}</ref>\n\n===Interim Welterweight Championship bout===\n{{Quote box| quote =Hughes is an amazing fighter. I just had a good night that night, and he had a bad night.\nIf we fight again, I don't think he's going to beat me, but he will probably come closer. Maybe he had a bad day -- it's a matter of circumstances as well.|align=right |width=40% |source=-[[Georges St-Pierre]].<ref name=\"GSP Afraid\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/articles/Weighty-Issues-10826 |title=Weighty Issues |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2008-01-16 |accessdate=2012-07-26 |last=Cotterill |first=Andy}}</ref>}}\n\nFollowing a championship win by [[Matt Serra]] over Georges St-Pierre at ''[[UFC 69]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/UFC-69-Shootout-4663 |title=UFC 69 - Shootout |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-09-05}}</ref> UFC President Dana White announced that Hughes would fight for the World Welterweight title in November 2007 against Serra.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/2468/report-serra-vs-hughes-to-headline-november-event-in-new-jersey.mma |title=Report: Serra vs. Hughes to Headline November Event in New Jersey |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |date=2007-06-20 |last=Stupp |first=Dann |accessdate=2012-09-05}}</ref> This fight was later changed to December 29, 2007, in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], at ''[[UFC 79|UFC 79: Nemesis]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/2615/ufc-headed-to-las-vegas-twice-in-december.mma |title=UFC Headed to Las Vegas Twice in December |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |date=2007-07-25 |last=Stupp |first=Dann |accessdate=2012-09-05 |authorlink=Dann Stupp}}</ref> On November 23, however, Serra sustained a herniated disc in his lower back and informed UFC that he would not be able to compete for an indeterminate time.<ref name=\"GSP rep\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/3231/injury-forces-matt-serra-off-ufc-79-fight-card.mma |title=Injury Forces Matt Serra off UFC 79 Fight Card |date=2007-11-23 |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |last=Stupp |first=Dann |accessdate=2012-09-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908034107/http://mmajunkie.com/news/3231/injury-forces-matt-serra-off-ufc-79-fight-card.mma |archivedate=2008-09-08 }}</ref> As a replacement for the title match, the UFC quickly signed a rubber match between Hughes and St-Pierre that would also be for the [[UFC Welterweight Championship|Interim UFC Welterweight Championship]].<ref name=\"GSP rep\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mmarising.com/news/11240701.html |title=St. Pierre to face Hughes at UFC 79 |publisher=MMARising.com |accessdate=2012-08-31 |last=Sargent |first=Robert}}</ref> Despite his best efforts, Hughes was unable to mount a serious offense on St-Pierre, who easily avoided Hughes' takedown attempts, while taking Hughes down at will and using Hughes' own ground-and-pound style against him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/3420/ufc-79-round-by-round-updates-and-live-results.mma |title=UFC 79 Round-by-round Updates and live results |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |last=Stupp |first=Dann |date=2007-12-29 |accessdate=2012-08-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015022825/http://mmajunkie.com/news/3420/ufc-79-round-by-round-updates-and-live-results.mma |archivedate=2012-10-15 }}</ref> Near the end of the second round, St-Pierre attempted a kimura on Hughes' right arm that he escaped, but in a reversal of their first fight, St-Pierre was able to twist it into a straight armbar with fifteen seconds remaining in the round.<ref name=\"UFC 79 Play-by-play\" /> Hughes fought the extension, but with his left hand trapped between the mat and St-Pierre's legs, was forced to verbally submit at 4:54 of the second round.<ref name=\"UFC 79 Play-by-play\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-79-Nemesis-Play-by-Play-10598 |title=UFC 79: Nemesis Play-by-play |publisher=Sherdog.com |accessdate=2012-07-19 |date=2007-12-29}}</ref> In the post-fight interview, Hughes praised St-Pierre as the better fighter:\n\n{{quote|No excuses here. I came into this fight 120 percent... Georges is the better fighter. There's nothing more I can say about it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/3421/ufc-79-georges-st-pierre-dominates-matt-hughes-for-interim-title-chuck-liddell-outlasts-wanderlei-silva.mma |title=GSP dominates Hughes, Liddell outlasts Silva |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |date=2007-12-30 |accessdate=2012-07-19 |last=Stupp |first=Dann |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510163045/http://mmajunkie.com/news/3421/ufc-79-georges-st-pierre-dominates-matt-hughes-for-interim-title-chuck-liddell-outlasts-wanderlei-silva.mma |archivedate=2012-05-10 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Hughes vs. Alves===\n{{Quote box | quote =This means everything to me. I remember watching Matt Hughes slamming people through the floor. I'm really, really happy.|source=\u2013[[Thiago Alves (fighter)|Thiago Alves]], on defeating Hughes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mma/news?slug=dd-ufceightyfive062609 |title=UFC 85: True bedlam |last=Doyle |first=Dave |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |date=2009-06-29 |accessdate=2012-07-21}}</ref> |align=right |width=40%}}\n\nHughes fought [[Thiago Alves (fighter)|Thiago Alves]] at ''[[UFC 85|UFC 85: BEDLAM]]'' on June 7, 2008. Hughes lost to Alves by TKO at 1:02 of the second round. After receiving a powerful flying knee, he dropped to the ground with his own left knee pinned behind his hips, ultimately leaving him with a torn [[Medial collateral ligament|MCL]] and partially torn [[Posterior cruciate ligament|PCL]]. Hughes took the fight on short notice as a favor to UFC. Alves failed to make weight for the match, but Hughes elected to fight him at a catch weight anyway.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/4524/ufc-85-recap-alves-rocks-hughes-bisping-cruises-to-tko-victory.mma |title=UFC 85 recap: Alves rocks Hughes, Bisping cruises TKO victory |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |accessdate=2012-05-21 |date=2008-06-07 |last=Stupp |first=Dann}}</ref> He stated in his blog:\n\n{{quote|Thiago came in big, some people told me that he looked bigger than me in the octagon. I didn't expect that but I also think that had nothing to do with the outcome of the fight. I think Thiago came up with a good game plan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/2008/06/09/thiago |title=Thiago |publisher=Matt-Hughes.com |date=2008-06-09 |accessdate=2012-07-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521170956/http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/2008/06/09/thiago/ |archive-date=2011-05-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\n===Hughes vs. Serra and future===\n{{Quote box | quote =In the future there are guys like [[Georges St-Pierre|GSP]] and Matt Hughes, who I'm sure are going to be hall-of-famers&nbsp;\u2014 Serra said before the event. - If I get Matt Hughes under my belt and take care of him, even if I would not be considered one of the best ever, I'd have some victories over some guys who will be. I can live with that.|align=right |width=40% |source=-[[Matt Serra]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/14974/after-ufc-98-nail-biter-matt-hughes-and-matt-serra-back-off-retirement-talk.mma |title=Matt Hughes and Matt Serra back off retirement talk |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |accessdate=2012-06-29 |date=2009-05-24 |last=Supp |first=Dann}}</ref>}}\n\nImmediately after the Alves fight, Hughes stated that he had \"one more fight\" left in him, and that he wanted to fight Matt Serra. Their rivalry stemmed from the time when Serra was a contestant on [[The Ultimate Fighter]] and Hughes was guest coach. Serra did not like the way Hughes criticized other contestants on the show and was disgusted when Hughes constantly picked on [[Georges St-Pierre]] during a lunch break and bragged about his submission victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LrGnG42ktVI |title=Matt Hughes OWNS GSP fanboy |publisher=YouTube.com |accessdate=2012-09-01 |date=2011-06-12}}</ref> On January 9, 2009, Hughes confirmed on his blog that ''[[UFC 98]]'' would likely be the day he and Serra met in the Octagon. UFC confirmed the fight.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/14150/ufc-officially-announces-ufc-98-lesnar-vs-mir-ii-for-may-23.mma |title=Hughes-Serra confirmed by UFC |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |date=2009-03-03 |accessdate=2012-07-19 |author=Staff}}</ref>\n\nHughes won the grudge match against Serra at ''UFC 98: Evans vs. Machida'' via unanimous decision.<ref name=\"UFC 98 Play-by-play\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Machida-KOs-Evans-Hughes-Outpoints-Serra-17607 |title=Machida KOs Evans; Hughes Outpoints Serra |publisher=Sherdog.com |last=Knapp |first=Brian |date=2009-05-24 |accessdate=2012-07-07}}</ref> In the first round, both fighters collided heads, and Hughes got the worst of it. Despite this, Serra could not finish the fight and Hughes recovered rapidly.<ref name=\"UFC 98 Play-by-play\" /> In the second round, Hughes controlled his opponent on the ground with his wrestling skills.<ref name=\"UFC 98 Play-by-play\" /> The final round saw the former champions taking each other down and exchanging punches.<ref name=\"UFC 98 Play-by-play\" /> The back and forth action rewarded both competitors with ''Fight of the Night'' honors.<ref name=\"FotN 2\">{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/14970/ufc-98-bonuses-hughes-serra-machida-and-larson-each-earn-60k-awards.mma/ |title=UFC 98 bonuses: Hughes, Serra, Machida and Larson each earn $60K |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |date=2009-05-24 |accessdate=2012-07-19 |author=Staff}}</ref> After the fight Hughes and Serra embraced each other and ended their feud. Hughes posted on his blog: \"When the fight was over, I was pretty confident I was going to get my hand raised. Some people have asked why I raised his hand at the end. Actually I didn't, he raised mine. He also told me that, no matter what the decision was, he was done with the rivalry\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/2009/05/25/ufc-98-recap/ |title=UFC 98 recap |last=Hughes |first=Matt |date=2009-05-25 |accessdate=2009-05-26 |publisher=Matt-Hughes.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090530133208/http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/2009/05/25/ufc-98-recap |archive-date=2009-05-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After the fight Hughes said, \"I think I have a few more fights left in me.\"\n\n===Hughes vs. Gracie===\nHughes then signed a multi-fight deal with the UFC.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/16076/matt-hughes-signs-multi-fight-last-contract-with-ufc-still-uncertain-of-next-bout.mma |title=Matt Hughes signs Multi-fight contract with UFC |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |accessdate=2012-09-01 |date=2009-09-03 |author=Staff}}</ref> Hughes defeated [[Renzo Gracie]], the 1st cousin once removed of his opponent at UFC 60, via third round [[technical knockout|TKO]] at ''[[UFC 112|UFC 112: Invincible]]'', setting the record for most UFC wins with 17.<ref name=\"Renzo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2010/04/10/ufc-112-matt-hughes-kos-renzo-gracie |title=Matt Hughes KO's Renzo Gracie |publisher=MMAFighting.com |date=2010-04-10 |last=Smith |first=Michael David |accessdate=2012-09-01}}</ref> Both of them seemed very comfortable fighting on their feet in the early going, with Gracie landing the cleaner and more effective punches and also landing a couple of kicks. Hughes started the second round with powerful leg kicks, but after that Gracie returned to his in-and-out punching style. Hughes got double underhooks and managed to take Gracie down briefly.<ref name=\"Renzo\" /> In the final round Hughes connected with a right hook to Gracie's chin, then connected with a leg kick and another punch. With two minutes to go he knocked Gracie down with a leg kick. Gracie took all the time he could before Hughes helped him up and then dropped him with a second leg kick. Gracie stalled again, but when he finally stood up Hughes floored him with a punch, let him get up and then attacked again. Hughes knocked Gracie down again with a fourth punch, when referee [[Herb Dean]] ended it.<ref name=\"Renzo\" />\n\n===Hall of Fame and Hughes vs. Almeida===\nOn May 28, 2010, Hughes was inducted into the [[UFC Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"mmamania.com\" /><ref name=\"BR Hall of Fame\" />\n\n{{quote|I never thought about this, to be honest - I'm just a Midwest guy kinda living the dream. But I'm very privileged and I thank the UFC. Shaking hands, signing autographs, being a world title holder and being inducted into the Hall of Fame, this is beyond what I ever would have pictured my life being.<ref name=\"Heavy\"/>}}\n\nFighting [[Renzo Gracie]] student and 3rd degree Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu black belt [[Ricardo Almeida]], Hughes rendered him unconscious with a [[Dave Schultz (wrestling)|Dave Schultz]] [[Headlock|front headlock]]<ref name=\"Front Headlock\" /> at 3:15 of round 1, on August 7, 2010 at ''[[UFC 117|UFC 117: Silva vs. Sonnen]]''.<ref name=\"Almeida\" /> Hughes landed a huge left hook that knocked Almeida down, sinking in the very deep choke which earned him the ''Submission of the Night'' honors.<ref name=\"SotN\">{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/20202/ufc-117-bonuses-struve-silva-sonnen-and-hughes-earn-60000-fighter-awards.mma |title=UFC 117 bonuses: Struve, Silva, Sonnen and Hughes earn $60,000 fighter awards |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |date=2012-08-08 |accessdate=2012-09-01 |author=Staff |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023073727/http://mmajunkie.com/news/20202/ufc-117-bonuses-struve-silva-sonnen-and-hughes-earn-60000-fighter-awards.mma |archivedate=2012-10-23 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-117-Bonuses-Silva-Sonnen-Hughes-Struve-Rewarded-26177 |title=UFC 117 Bonuses: Silva, Sonnen, Hughes, Struve Rewarded |date=2010-08-07 |accessdate=2012-09-01 |publisher=Sherdog.com |last=Knapp |first=Brian}}</ref> Almeida requested the fight after watching his mentor lose to Hughes at ''UFC 112'' back in April. Hughes now had four wins over mixed martial artists with ties to the Gracies, including UFC pioneer Royce Gracie, the prior mentioned Renzo Gracie and former champ Serra.<ref name=\"Almeida\" />\n\n{{quote|It's an old-school wrestling move. I've been good at it. I'm happy to beat a good Brazilian with a wrestling move.<ref name=\"Almeida\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/mma/post/2010/08/matt-hughes-chokes-ricardo-almeida-unconscious-/1\n|title=Matt Hughes chokes Ricardo Almeida unconscious\n|publisher=USA TODAY\n|date=2010-08-07\n|accessdate=2012-07-19\n|author=Non, Sergio}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Hughes vs. Penn III===\n{{Quote box| quote =You're my idol -- Matt Hughes, you're my idol, you will always be my idol, thank you.|align=right |width=30% |source=-[[B.J. Penn]] at the post-fight interview.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tapology.com/fightcenter/bouts/ufc-123-matt-hughes-vs-bj-the-prodigy-penn-iii-3|title=BJ Penn vs. Matt Hughes III |publisher=Tapology.com |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref>}}\n\nHughes faced [[BJ Penn]] on November 20, 2010, in a rubber match at ''[[UFC 123|UFC 123: Rampage vs. Machida]]'', after their previous two fights at ''[[UFC 46]]'' and ''[[UFC 63]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2010/09/13/matt-hughes-bj-penn-to-complete-trilogy-at-ufc-123-in-michigan/|title=Matt Hughes, BJ Penn to Complete Trilogy at UFC 123 in Michigan |publisher=MMAFighting.com |accessdate=2010-09-13 |date=2010-09-13 |last=Tucker |first=Bryan}}</ref> Penn came out strong in the first few seconds of the opening round, catching one of Hughes' kicks and knocking him off balance with a counter hook. Penn then connected with an overhand right that dropped Hughes, following up with three clean shots to the jaw.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2010/11/20/b-j-penn-kos-matt-hughes-at-ufc-123 |title=B.J. Penn KOs Matt Hughes at UFC 123 |publisher=MMAFighting.com |date=2010-11-20 |accessdate=2012-09-01 |last=Smith |first=Michael David}}</ref> The bout was ended at 21 seconds into the first round, with Hughes trilogy against Penn ending at 1-2. The fight marked the first time Hughes had been knocked out (he had previously lost via technical knockout). Post-fight Hughes hinted that the loss moved him one step closer to retirement.\n\n{{quote|I had a lot on the line. This was a huge fight for me. To be honest, I don't know what goes on now.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/writers/ben_fowlkes/11/23/ufc.113/index.html |title=Matt Hughes looks to regroup after knockout loss to B.J. Penn |publisher=Sports Illustrated |date=2010-11-23 |last=Fowlkes |first=Ben |accessdate=2012-09-01}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Hughes vs. Koscheck===\nHughes was expected to face [[Diego Sanchez]] on September 24, 2011 at ''[[UFC 135|UFC 135: Jones vs. Rampage]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/23925/matt-hughes-vs-diego-sanchez-expected-for-ufc-135-in-denver.mma |title=Matt Hughes vs. Diego Sanchez expected for UFC 135 in Denver |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |accessdate=2012-06-08 |date=2011-06-08 |author=Staff |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218012845/http://mmajunkie.com/news/23925/matt-hughes-vs-diego-sanchez-expected-for-ufc-135-in-denver.mma |archivedate=2012-02-18 }}</ref> However, Sanchez missed the bout with an injury and was replaced by [[Josh Koscheck]].<ref name=\"KosIn\">{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/25114/matt-hughes-vs-josh-koscheck-official-for-ufc-135-in-denver.mma |title=Matt Hughes vs. Josh Koscheck official for UFC 135 in Denver |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |date=2011-09-06 |accessdate=2012-09-01 |author=Staff |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614025203/http://mmajunkie.com/news/25114/matt-hughes-vs-josh-koscheck-official-for-ufc-135-in-denver.mma |archivedate=2012-06-14 }}</ref> Hughes suffered a KO loss to Koscheck at 4:59 of the first round. Hughes showed improved striking, but ultimately succumbed to Koscheck's power punches.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmafrenzy.com/24476/ufc-135-results-josh-koscheck-kos-matt-hughes-in-first-hughes-not-retiring/ |title=Koscheck KOs Hughes in First, Hughes Not Retiring |publisher=MMAFrenzy.com |date=2011-09-24 |accessdate=2012-07-20 |last=Karkoski |first=Kris}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|I'm not retiring. I'm just going to tell the UFC to put me up on a shelf for a while, and we'll see what happens after that.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Erickson |first1=Matt |last2=Morgan |first2=John |title=UFC 135 main-card results: Jones chokes out 'Rampage,' Koscheck KOs Hughes |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/25390/ufc-135-main-card-results-jones-chokes-out-rampage-koschecks-kos-hughes.mma |publisher=[[MMAjunkie.com]] |accessdate=2011-09-25 |date=2011-09-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927055937/http://mmajunkie.com/news/25390/ufc-135-main-card-results-jones-chokes-out-rampage-koschecks-kos-hughes.mma |archivedate=2011-09-27 }}</ref>}}\n\n===Retirement===\nThe UFC announced on January 24, 2013 that Matt Hughes retired from fighting and was named a Vice President of Athlete Development and Government Relations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Top MMA News Staff |title=Matt Hughes Retires, Promoted to UFC Vice President |url=http://topmmanews.com/2013/01/24/matt-hughes-retires-promoted-to-ufc-vice-president/ |publisher=Top MMA News |accessdate=2013-01-24 |date=2013-01-24}}</ref>\n\n===Theme music===\nIn the UFC, Hughes frequently used the song \"[[A Country Boy Can Survive]]\" by [[Hank Williams, Jr.]] as he made his entrance towards the Octagon. At the ''[[UFC 56]]'' live broadcast, [[Joe Rogan]] said: \"My favorite walk-out song in all the UFC, \u2032A country boy can survive.\u2032\"<ref>{{cite video |title=[[UFC 56|UFC 56: Full Force]] |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] |location=[[Las Vegas, Nevada]], [[United States]] |date=2006-11-19}}</ref>\n\n==Autobiography==\n\nHughes released his autobiography, ''Made in America: The Most Dominant Champion in UFC History'', co-written with [[Michael Malice]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matt-hughes.com/blog1/?page_id=617 |title=Autobiography |accessdate=2012-06-20 |publisher=Matt-Hughes.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091214055614/http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/?page_id=617 |archivedate=2009-12-14 }}</ref> on January 1, 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmamania.com/2007/12/07/matt-hughes-new-book-made-in-america-the-most-dominant-champion-in-ufc-history-set-for-2008-release/ |title=Matt Hughes new book 'Made in America: The Most Dominant Champion in UFC History' set for 2008 release |publisher=MMAmania.com |date=2007-12-07 |accessdate=2012-09-02 |author=Staff}}</ref> The book debuted at #21 on the [[New York Times bestseller list]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/27/books/bestseller/0127besthardnonfiction.html |title=Hardcover Nonfiction New York Times bestseller list |date=2008-01-27|publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=2012-09-02}}</ref>\n\n==Television Series==\n\n===''Trophy Hunters TV''===\nSince January 2011, Hughes is the host of [[hunting]] program Trophy Hunters TV, which airs in [[Outdoor Channel]] three times a week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/trophy-hunters-tv/ |title=Trophy Hunters TV |last=Hughes |first=Matt |publisher=Matt-Hughes.com |accessdate=2012-07-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508184648/http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/trophy-hunters-tv/ |archive-date=2012-05-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://outdoorchannel.com/Shows/TrophyHuntersTV/Hosts.aspx |title=Trophy Hunters TV: Meet The Host |publisher=OutdoorChannel.com |accessdate=2012-07-15}}</ref> The show is closely related to the Texas Trophy Hunters Association.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ttha.com/tv-magazine/trophy-hunters-tv |title=Trophy Hunters TV |accessdate=2012-07-15 |publisher=Texas Trophy Hunters Association}}</ref>\n\n===''Uncaged with Matt Hughes''===\nOn July 4, 2014, Hughes became the host of ''Uncaged with Matt Hughes'', which airs Saturdays on the [[Sportsman Channel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2014/10/11/6962615/ufc-fighter-matt-hughes-tv-mini-series-uncaged-sportsman-channel-african-hunting-safari-mma-news|title=Matt Hughes gets TV mini series \"Uncaged\" for African hunting safari}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesportsmanchannel.com/shows/uncaged-with-matt-hughes/|title=Uncaged with Matt Hughes|access-date=2014-10-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141024001918/http://www.thesportsmanchannel.com/shows/uncaged-with-matt-hughes/|archive-date=2014-10-24|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms==\nHughes has been criticized by animal advocates, including former UFC fighter and commentator [[Dan Hardy]], for his [[trophy hunting]].<ref name=\"Helwani\">{{cite web|last=Helwani|first=Ariel|title=Dan Hardy talks retirement, says Matt Hughes is 'bad for the sport'|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2013/2/9/3967098/dan-hardy-talks-retirement-says-matt-hughes-is-bad-for-the-sport|work=MMAfighting.com|publisher=VOX Media|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> In response to outrage over trophy hunting pictures posted on his Twitter account in 2012, Hughes called some of the commenters \"PETA idiots\" and told them to stop following his page.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matt Hughes in bitter twitter quarrel with 'PETA idiots'|url=http://www.mixedmartialarts.com/news/375353/Matt-Hughes-in-bitter-twitter-quarrel-with-PETA-idiots/|work=MixedMartialArts.com|publisher=Mixed Martial Arts LLC|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHughes is a [[Born again (Christianity)|born again Christian]] and regularly posts Bible verses on his website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.matt-hughes.com/ |title=9-Time UFC Welterweight Champion |publisher=Matt-Hughes.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-11}}</ref> Hughes and his wife Audra have two daughters together and Audra has a son from a previous relationship.<ref name=\"mattchild\" /> The couple's second daughter was born on January 2, 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/?p=724 |title=Katelyn Mae Hughes |accessdate=2010-01-05 |publisher=Matt-Hughes.com |date=2010-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110062613/http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/?p=724 |archivedate=2010-01-10 }}</ref> Matt and his twin brother were born on their father's birthday.<ref name=\"13 Oct 1973\">{{cite web |url=http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/2011/10/12/happy-birthday-matt-and-mark-3/ |title=Happy Birthday Matt and Mark! |publisher=Matt-Hughes.com |date=2011-10-12 |accessdate=2012-07-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625085156/http://matt-hughes.com/blog1/2011/10/12/happy-birthday-matt-and-mark-3/ |archivedate=2012-06-25 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 16, 2017, Hughes was hospitalized with a serious head injury after a train struck the passenger side of his truck at a [[Level Crossing#Crossing identification|rail crossing]] near his home in [[Montgomery County, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kwqc.com/content/news/UFC-Hall-of-Fame-Member-Matt-Hughes-seriously-injured-in-Truck-vs-Train-Accident-428919953.html |title=UFC Hall of Famer Matt Hughes seriously injured in truck vs. train accident |publisher=kwqc.com|date=2017-06-17 |accessdate=2017-06-17 |last=Stratton |first=James}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/08/matt-hughes-rolling-on-mat-instagram-video-truck-train-accident-recovery|title=From scary accident to coma to rolling, UFC Hall of Famer Matt Hughes is back on the mat|website=mmajunkie|author=Blue Corner|date=2017-08-22|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref> On June 18, Hughes' family released a statement that he had no broken bones or internal injuries but was unconscious and unresponsive.  They were working with the Triumph Over Tragedy Foundation to determine next steps for care. The Foundation, of which Hughes was a board member for five years, provides care for families with brain and spinal cord injuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Matt-Hughes-Family-Working-with-Brain-and-Spinal-Injury-NonProfit-Organization-123581|title=Matt Hughes' Family Working with Brain and Spinal Injury Non-Profit Organization|last=Sherdog.com|website=Sherdog|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref> Hughes recovered from his injury and on October 4, 2017 he returned to the  hospital to honor the hospital staff who took care of him while he was there.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2017/10/4/16423970/ufc-legend-matt-hughes-returns-to-hospital-to-honor-nurses-who-treated-him-after-crash|title=VIDEO: UFC legend Matt Hughes returns to hospital to honor nurses who treated him after crash|work=MMA Fighting|access-date=2017-10-05}}</ref> On 14 January 2018, Hughes returned ringside as a guest of honor during [[UFC Fight Night: Stephens vs. Choi|UFC Fight Night]] in [[St. Louis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ufc/status/952747038118051840|title=Welcome home, Matt Hughes. #UFCSTLpic.twitter.com/2CH5mB3DGH|last=UFC|date=7:39 PM - 14 Jan 2018|website=@ufc|language=en|access-date=2018-01-15}}</ref> On September 19, 2019, news surfaced that Hughes sued [[Norfolk Southern Railway]] and several of its employees for the 2017 train crash.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/9/19/20873136/matt-hughes-suing-train-operator-at-center-of-near-fatal-accident|title=Matt Hughes suing train operator at center of near-fatal accident|author=Steven Marrocco|publisher=mmafighting.com|date=September 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic violence allegations===\nIn February 2019 Hughes was given a restraining order by his wife after she accused him of several incidents of domestic violence. His brother [[Mark Hughes (fighter)|Mark Hughes]] also filed a restraining order against him claiming that Matt choked his son and tried to destroy his tractor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tmz.com/2019/02/26/ufc-matt-hughes-domestic-violence-restraining-order/|title=UFC'S MATT HUGHES HIT WITH RESTRAINING ORDER WIFE CLAIMS DOMESTIC VIOLENCE|publisher=[[TMZ]]|author=Staff|date=2019-02-26|accessdate=2019-02-26}}</ref> Hughes filed to divorce his wife on February 21, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/2/26/18241622/wife-of-ufc-hall-of-famer-matt-hughes-granted-order-of-protection-against-her-husband|title=Wife of UFC Hall of Famer Matt Hughes granted order of protection against her husband|date=February 26, 2019|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Alexander K. Lee}}</ref> In August 2019, Hughes's attorneys revealed that the brothers had settled the case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2019/09/matt-hughes-settles-tractor-dispute-twin-brother-mark-ufc|title=UFC Hall of Famer Matt Hughes settles tractor dispute with twin brother Mark|author=Steven Marrocco|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=September 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and achievements==\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Mixed martial arts===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*'''[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]'''\n**[[UFC Hall of Fame]] (Pioneer Wing, class of 2010) and (Fight Wing, class of 2015) <small>vs. [[Frank Trigg]] at [[UFC 52]]</small>\n**[[List of UFC champions#UFC Welterweight champion|UFC Welterweight Championship]] (Two times)<ref name=\"Milestones\">{{cite web |url=http://lowkick.blitzcorner.com/UFC/Matt-Hughes-inducted-into-the-UFC-Hall-of-Fame-7977 |title=Matt Hughes inducted into the UFC Hall of Fame |publisher=LowKick.com |date=2010-05-29 |accessdate=2012-09-25 |last=Gurevich |first=Anton |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111219215708/http://lowkick.blitzcorner.com/UFC/Matt-Hughes-inducted-into-the-UFC-Hall-of-Fame-7977 |archivedate=2011-12-19 }}</ref>\n**Five successful title defenses (first reign)\n**Two successful title defenses (second reign)\n**Seven successful title defenses (overall)<ref name=\"Milestones\"/>\n**[[Bonus Awards|Fight of the Night]] (Two times)<ref name=\"FotN 1\"/><ref name=\"FotN 2\"/>\n**[[Bonus Awards|Submission of the Night]] (One time)<ref name=\"SotN\"/>\n**Second most title defenses in the UFC welterweight division (Seven)\n**Second most title fights in